# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-species-iucn-status
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The **Amazon river dolphin** (***Inia geoffrensis***), also known as the **boto**, **bufeo** or **pink river dolphin**, is a species of toothed whale endemic to South America and is classified in the family Iniidae.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Three subspecies are currently recognized: *I. g. geoffrensis* (Amazon river dolphin), *I. g. boliviensis* (Bolivian river dolphin) and *I. g. humboldtiana* (Orinoco river dolphin).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The position of the Araguaian river dolphin (*I. araguaiaensis*) within the clade is still unclear.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The three subspecies are distributed in the Amazon basin, the upper Madeira River in Bolivia, and the Orinoco basin, respectively.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Amazon river dolphin is the largest species of river dolphin, with many adult males reaching 185 kilograms (408 lb) in weight, and 2.5 metres (8.2 ft) in length.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Adults acquire a pink color, more prominent in males, giving it its nickname "pink river dolphin".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Sexual dimorphism is very evident, with males measuring 16% longer and weighing 55% more than females.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Like other toothed whales, they have a melon, an organ that is used for bio sonar.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The dorsal fin, although short in height, is regarded as long, and the pectoral fins are also large.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The fin size, unfused vertebrae, and its relative size allow for improved maneuverability when navigating flooded forests and capturing prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They have one of the widest-ranging diets among toothed whales, and feed on up to 53 different species of fish, such as croakers, catfish, tetras and piranhas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They also consume other animals such as river turtles, aquatic frogs, and freshwater crabs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In 2018, this species was ranked by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) as endangered, with a declining population.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Threats include incidental catch in fishing lines, direct hunting for use as fishing bait or predator control, damming, and pollution.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Until 2025, it was the only species of river dolphin kept in captivity, mainly in South American countries like Venezuela.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It was said to be difficult to train, and had a high mortality rate among captive individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The species *Inia geoffrensis* was described by Henri Marie Ducrotay de Blainville in 1817.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Originally, the Amazon river dolphin belonged to the superfamily Platanistoidea, which constituted all river dolphins, making them a paraphyletic group.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Today, however, the Amazon river dolphin has been reclassified into the superfamily Inioidea.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] There is no consensus on when and how their ancestral species penetrated the Amazon basin; they may have done so during the Miocene from the Pacific Ocean, before the formation of the Andes, or from the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] There is ongoing debate about the classification of species and subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The IUCN and Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy recognize two subspecies: *I. g. geoffrensis* (Amazon river dolphin) and *I. g. boliviensis* (Bolivian river dolphin).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] A third proposed subspecies, *I. g. humboldtiana* (Orinoco river dolphin), was first described in 1977.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Molecular analysis suggests that the Orinoco dolphins are derived from the Amazon population and are not genetically distinct.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Comparative morphological research also indicates that *I. g. humboldtiana* is not distinguishable from *I. g. geoffrensis*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, Cañizales (2020) found that *I. g. humboldtiana* skulls were morphologically distinct and recommended that it be elevated to species status.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In 2012, it was proposed that *I. g. boliviensis* was a different species based on skull morphology.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] A recent study, with more comprehensive sampling of the Madeira system, including above and below the Teotonio Rapids (which were thought to obstruct gene flow), found that the *Inia* above the rapids did not possess unique mtDNA.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] As such the species level distinction once held is not supported by current results.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Therefore, the Bolivian river dolphin is currently recognized as a subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In addition, a 2014 study identifies a third species in the Araguaia-Tocantins basin, but this designation is not recognized by any international organization and the Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy suggests this analysis is not persuasive.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Amazon river dolphin is the largest river dolphin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It has very evident sexual dimorphism, with males measuring and weighing between 16% and 55% more than females, making it unique among river dolphins, where females are generally larger than males.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The texture of the body is robust and strong but flexible.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Unlike in oceanic dolphins, the cervical vertebrae are not fused, allowing the head to turn 90 degrees.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The flukes are broad and triangular, and the dorsal fin, which is keel-shaped, is short in height but very long, extending from the middle of the body to the caudal region.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The pectoral fins are large and paddle-shaped.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The length of its fins allows the animal to perform a circular movement, allowing for exceptional maneuverability to swim through the flooded forest but decreasing its speed.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Newborns and the young have a dark grey tint, which in adolescence transforms into light grey, and in adults turns pink as a result of repeated abrasion of the skin surface.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Males tend to be pinker than females due to more frequent trauma from intra-species aggression.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The color of adults varies between solid and mottled pink and in some adults the dorsal surface is darker.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It is believed that the difference in color depends on the temperature, water transparency, and geographical location.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] There was one albino on record, kept in Duisburg Zoo's dolphinarium.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, as of 2020, this specimen and one other have died.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The skull of the species is slightly asymmetrical compared to the other toothed whales.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It has a long, thin snout, with 25 to 28 pairs of long and slender teeth to each side of both jaws.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Dentition is heterodont, meaning that the teeth differ in shape and length, with differing functions for both grabbing and crushing prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Anterior teeth are conical and later have ridges on the inside of the crown.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Despite small eyes, the species seems to have good eyesight in and out of the water.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It has a melon on the head, the shape of which can be modified by muscular control when used for biosonar.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Breathing takes place every 30 to 110 seconds.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In the wild, the life expectancy of the Amazon river dolphin is unknown, but in captivity, the longevity of healthy individuals has been recorded at between 10 and 30 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] According to a 1986 study of the average longevity of this species in captivity, the lifespan of this species in the United States was only 33 months.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Until his death in December 2020, an individual named "Baby" lived up to (at least) 46 years at the Duisburg Zoo in Germany.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] At the time of his death, he had lived at Duisburg Zoo for 45 years and 9 months.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Amazon river dolphin are commonly seen singly or in pairs, but may also occur in pods that rarely contain more than eight individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Pods as large as 37 individuals have been seen in the Amazon, but the average is three.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In the Orinoco, the largest observed groups number 30, but the average is just above five.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] During prey time, as many as 35 pink dolphins work together to obtain their prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Typically, social bonds occur between mother and child, but may also been seen in heterogeneous groups or bachelor groups.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The largest congregations are seen in areas with abundant food, and at the mouths of rivers.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] There is significant segregation during the rainy season, with males occupying the river channels, while females and their offspring are located in flooded areas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, in the dry season, there is no such separation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Due to the high level of prey fish, larger group-sizes are seen in large sections that are directly influenced by whitewater (such as main rivers and lakes, especially during low water season) than in smaller sections influenced by blackwater (such as channels and smaller tributaries).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In their freshwater habitat they are apex predators and gatherings depend more on food sources and habitat availability than in oceanic dolphins where protection from larger predators is necessary.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Captive studies have shown that the Amazon river dolphin is less shy than the bottlenose dolphin, but also less sociable.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It is very curious and has a remarkable lack of fear of foreign objects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, dolphins in captivity may not show the same behavior that they do in their natural environment, where they have been reported to hold the oars of fishermen, rub against boats, pluck underwater plants, and play with sticks, logs, clay, turtles, snakes, and fish.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They are slow swimmers; they commonly travel at speeds of 1.5 to 3.2 kilometres per hour (0.93 to 1.99 mph) but have been recorded to swim at speeds up to 14 to 22 kilometres per hour (8.7 to 13.7 mph).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] When they surface, the tips of the snout, melon and dorsal fins appear simultaneously, the tail rarely showing before diving.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They can also shake their fins, and pull their tail fin and head above the water to observe the environment.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They occasionally jump out of the water, sometimes as high as a meter (3.14 ft).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They are harder to train than most other species of dolphin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Adult males have been observed carrying objects in their mouths such as branches or other floating vegetation, or balls of hardened clay.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The males appear to carry these objects as a socio-sexual display which is part of their mating system.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The behavior is "triggered by an unusually large number of adult males and/or adult females in a group, or perhaps it attracts such into the group.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Later, it was shown that males were larger than females and are documented wielding an aggressive sexual behavior in the wild and in captivity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Males often have a significant degree of damage in the dorsal, caudal, and pectoral fins, as well as the blowhole, due to bites and abrasions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They also commonly have numerous secondary teeth-raking scars.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This suggests fierce competition for access to females, with a polygynous mating system, though polyandry and promiscuity cannot be excluded.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In captivity, courtship and mating foreplay have been documented.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The male takes the initiative by nibbling the fins of the female, but reacts aggressively if the female is not receptive.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] A high frequency of copulations in a couple was observed; they used three different positions: contacting the womb at right angles, lying head to head, or head to tail.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Breeding is seasonal, and births occur between May and June.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The period of birthing coincides with the flood season, and this may provide an advantage because the females and their offspring remain in flooded areas longer than males.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] As the water level begins to decrease, the density of food sources in flooded areas increases due to loss of space, providing enough energy for infants to meet the high demands required for growth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Gestation is estimated to be around eleven months and captive births take 4 to 5 hours.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] At birth, calves are 80 centimetres (31 in) long and in captivity have registered a growth of 0.21 metres (0.69 ft) per year.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The interval between births is estimated between 15 and 36 months, and the young dolphins are thought to become independent within two to three years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The relatively long duration of breastfeeding and parenting suggests a high level of parental care.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Most couples observed in their natural environment consist of a female and her calf.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This suggests that long periods of parental care contribute to learning and development of the young.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The diet of the Amazon river dolphin is the most diverse of the toothed whales.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It consists of at least 53 different species of fish, grouped in 19 families.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The prey size is between 5 and 80 centimetres (2.0 and 31.5 in), with an average of 20 centimetres (7.9 in).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The most frequently consumed fish belong to the families Sciaenidae (croakers), Cichlidae (cichlids), Characidae (characins and tetras), and Serrasalmidae (pacus, piranhas and silver dollars).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The dolphin's dentition allows it to access shells of river turtles (such as *Podocnemis sextuberculata*) and freshwater crabs (such as *Poppiana argentiniana*).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The diet is more diverse during the wet season, when fish are spread in flooded areas outside riverbeds, thus becoming more difficult to catch.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The diet becomes more selective during the dry season when prey density is greater.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Usually, these dolphins are active and feeding throughout the day and night.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, they are predominantly crepuscular.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They consume about 5.5% of their body weight per day.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They sometimes take advantage of the disturbances made by boats to catch disoriented prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Sometimes, they associate with the distantly related tucuxi (*Sotalia fluviatilis*), and giant otters (*Pteronura brasiliensis*) to hunt in a coordinated manner, by gathering and attacking fish stocks at the same time.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Apparently, there is little competition for food between these species, as each prefers different prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] It has also been observed that captive dolphins share food.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Amazonian rivers are often very murky, and the Amazon river dolphin is therefore likely to depend much more on its sense of echolocation than vision when navigating and finding prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, echolocation in shallow waters and flooded forests may result in many echoes to keep track of.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] For each click produced a multitude of echoes are likely to return to the echolocating animal almost on top of each other which makes object discrimination difficult.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This may be why the Amazon river dolphin produces less powerful clicks compared to other similar sized toothed whales.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] By sending out clicks of lower amplitude only nearby objects will cast back detectable echoes, and hence fewer echoes need to be sorted out, but the cost is a reduced biosonar range.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This in turn allow these animals to have a high acoustic update rate on their surroundings which may aid prey tracking when echolocating in shallow rivers and flooded forests with plenty of hiding places for the prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] While preying in murky water, they emit series of clicking noises, 30 to 80 per second, and use the returning echos to locate their prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Like other dolphins, river dolphins use whistling tones to communicate.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The issuance of these sounds is related to the time they return to the surface before diving, suggesting a link to food.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Acoustic analysis revealed that the vocalisations are different in structure from the typical whistles of other species of dolphins.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Male Amazon river dolphins have been observed to exhibit an unusual aerial urination behavior, predominantly in social contexts involving other males.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] During these events, a urinating male positions itself upside down, ejecting a urine stream into the air, while a receiving male actively seeks the stream with its rostrum, possibly detecting chemical signals through specialized bristles.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Researchers speculate that this behavior likely serves a social or communicative function beyond waste elimination, potentially facilitating chemical communication in a species with limited olfactory capabilities.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Amazon river dolphins are the most widespread river dolphins.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They are present in six countries in South America: Bolivia, Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela, in an area covering about 7 million square kilometres (2.7 million square miles).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The boundaries are set by waterfalls, such as the Xingu and Tapajós rivers in Brazil, as well as very shallow water.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] A series of rapids and waterfalls in the Madeira River have isolated one population, recognized as the subspecies *I. g. boliviensis*, in the southern part of the Amazon basin in Bolivia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They are also distributed in the basin of the Orinoco River, except the Caroni River and the upper Caura River in Venezuela.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The only connection between the Orinoco and the Amazon is through the Casiquiare canal.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The distribution of dolphins in the rivers and surrounding areas depends on the time of year; in the dry season they are located in the river beds, but in the rainy season, when the rivers overflow, they disperse to the flooded areas, both the forests and the plains.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Studies to estimate the population are difficult to analyze due to the difference in the methodology used.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In a study conducted in the stretch of the Amazon called Solimões River, with a length of 1,200 kilometres (750 mi) between the cities of Manaus and Tabatinga, a total of 332 individuals was sighted ± 55 per inspection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Density was estimated at 0.08–0.33 animals per square kilometer in the main channels, and 0.49 to 0.93 animals per square kilometer in the branches.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In another study, on a stretch of 120 kilometres (75 mi) at the confluence of Colombia, Brazil and Peru, 345 individuals with a density of 4.8 per square km in the tributaries around the islands.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] 2.7 and 2.0 were observed along the banks.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Additionally, another study was conducted in the Amazon at the height of the mouth of the Caqueta River for six days.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] As a result of the studies conducted, it was found that the density is higher in the riverbanks, 3.7 per km, decreasing towards the center of the river.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In studies conducted during the rainy season, the density observed in the flood plain was 18 animals per square km, while on the banks of rivers and lakes ranged from 1.8 to 5.8 individuals per square km.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] These observations suggest that the Amazon river dolphin is found in higher density than any other cetacean.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Amazon river dolphin is located in most of the area's aquatic habitats, including; river basins, major courses of rivers, canals, river tributaries, lakes, and at the ends of rapids and waterfalls.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Cyclical changes in the water levels of rivers take place throughout the year.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] During the dry season, dolphins occupy the main river channels, and during the rainy season, they can move easily to smaller tributaries, to the forest, and to floodplains.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In the Pacaya-Samiria National Reserve, Peru, photo-identification is used to recognize individuals based on pigmentation patterns, scars and abnormalities in the beak.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] 72 individuals were recognized, of which 25 were again observed between 1991 and 2000.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The intervals between sightings ranged from one day to 7.5 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The maximum range of motion was 220 kilometres (140 mi), with an average of 60.8 kilometres (37.8 mi).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The longest distance in one day was 120 kilometres (75 mi), with an average of 14.5 kilometres (9.0 mi).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In a previous study conducted at the center of the Amazon River, a dolphin was observed that moved only a few dozen kilometers from the dry season and wet season.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, three of the reviewed 160 animals were observed over 100 kilometres (62 mi) from where they were first registered.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Research in 2011 concluded that photo-identification by skilled operatives using high-quality digital equipment could be a useful tool in monitoring population size, movements and social patterns.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Historically, this species had been kept across select zoos and dolphinariums.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Several hundred individuals were captured between the 1950s and the mid-1970s, and were distributed throughout the United States, Europe, and Japan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In the USA alone, over 70 were directly imported, and of those individuals, only 20 would survive.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] On February 20 2002, "Chuckles", a 34-year-old male, died at the Pittsburgh Zoo & Aquarium as the last of his species in the United States.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The region of the Amazon in Brazil has an extension of 5,000,000 km2 (1,900,000 mi2) containing diverse fundamental ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] One of these ecosystems is a floodplain, or a várzea forest, and is home to a large number of fish species which are an essential resource for human consumption.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The várzea is also a major source of income through excessive local commercialized fishing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Várzea consists of muddy river waters containing a vast number and diversity of nutrient rich species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The abundance of distinct fish species lures the Amazon River dolphin into the várzea areas of high water occurrences during the seasonal flooding.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In addition to attracting predators such as the Amazon river dolphin, these high-water occurrences are an ideal location to draw in the local fisheries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Human fishing activities directly compete with the dolphins for the same fish species, the tambaqui (*Colossoma macropomum*) and the pirapitinga (*Piaractus brachypomus*), resulting in deliberate or unintentional catches of the Amazon river dolphin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The local fishermen overfish and when the Amazon River dolphins are removed from the commercial catch in the nets and lines, it causes damages to the equipment and the capture, as well as generating ill will from the local fishermen.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The negative reactions of the local fishermen are also attributed to the Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources prohibition on killing the Amazon river dolphin, yet not compensating the fishermen for the damage done to their equipment and catch.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] During the process of catching the commercialized fish, the Amazon river dolphins get caught in the nets and exhaust themselves until they die, or the local fishermen deliberately kill the entangled dolphins.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The carcasses are discarded, consumed, or used as bait to attract a scavenger catfish, the piracatinga (*Calophysus macropterus*).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The use of the Amazon river dolphin carcass as bait for the piracatinga dates back to 2000.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Increasing demand for the piracatinga has created a market for distribution of the Amazon river dolphin carcasses to be used as bait throughout these regions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Of the 15 dolphin carcasses found in the Japurá River in 2010–2011 surveys, 73% of the dolphins were killed for bait, disposed of, or abandoned in entangled gillnets.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The data do not fully represent the actual overall number of deaths of the Amazon river dolphins, whether accidental or intentional, because a variety of factors make it extremely complicated to record and medically examine all the carcasses.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Scavenger species feed upon the carcasses, and the complexity of the river currents make it nearly impossible to locate all of the dead animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] More importantly, the local fishermen do not report these deaths out of fear that a legal course of action will be taken against them, as the Amazon river dolphin and other cetaceans are protected under a Brazilian federal law prohibiting any takes, harassments, and kills of the species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Amazon river suffers from pollution by mercury from industrial and mining sources.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] High mercury concentrations were found in muscle tissue from a male Amazon river dolphin in the Tapajos River (Brazil), and in the body and milk of female dolphins.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In September 2023, 154 Amazon river dolphins died in Brazil's Lake Tefé following record-high water temperatures of 40 °C (104 °F) and reduced water levels during a drought.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] While there are ongoing studies by the Mamirauá Institute for Sustainable Development to determine the cause of the deaths, the leading hypothesis is that the elevated temperature caused algae in the lake to release a toxin that attacks the central nervous system.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In 2008, the International Whaling Commission (IWC) expressed concern for captured botos for use as bait in the Central Amazon, which is an emerging problem that has spread on a large scale.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] According to a previous assessment by the Scientific Committee of the International Whaling Commission in 2000, the population of botos appears great and there is little or no evidence of population decline in numbers and range.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] However, increased human intervention on their habitat is expected to, in the future, be the most likely cause of the decline of its range and population.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In September 2012, Bolivian President Evo Morales enacted a law to protect the dolphin and declared it a national treasure.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In 2018, the species was listed on the Red list of endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Increasing pollution and gradual destruction of the Amazon rainforest add to the vulnerability of the species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The biggest threats are deforestation and other human activities that contribute to disrupt and alter their environment.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Another source of concern is the difficulty in keeping these animals alive in captivity, due to intra-species aggression and low longevity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Captive breeding is not considered a conservation option for this species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The Global Declaration for River Dolphins seeks to reverse the decline of river dolphin populations throughout the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] As of early 2024, 11 of the 14 countries that have river dolphins have signed the declaration.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In traditional Amazon River folklore, at night, an Amazon river dolphin becomes a handsome young man who seduces girls, impregnates them, and then returns to the river in the morning to become a dolphin again.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Similarly, the female becomes a beautiful, well-dressed, wealthy-looking young woman.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This dolphin shapeshifter is called an *encantado*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] The myth has been suggested to have arisen partly because dolphin genitalia bear a resemblance to those of humans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Others believe the myth served (and still serves) as a way of hiding the incestuous relations which are quite common in some small, isolated communities along the river.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In the area, tales relate it is bad luck to kill a dolphin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Legend also states that if a person makes eye contact with an Amazon river dolphin, they will have lifelong nightmares.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] According to the pink Amazon river dolphin myth, it is said that this creature takes form of a human and seduces men and women to the Underworld of Encante.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] This underworld place is said to be 'Atlantis-like Paradise', yet no one has come back from it alive.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Myths say that whoever kills the amazon dolphin will have bad luck, but it's worse for whoever eats it.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Local legends also state that the dolphin is the guardian of the Amazonian manatee, and that if one should wish to find a manatee, one must first make peace with the dolphin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] Associated with these legends is the use of various fetishes, such as dried eyeballs and genitalia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] These may or may not be accompanied by the intervention of a shaman.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] A recent study has shown, despite the claim of the seller and the belief of the buyers, none of these fetishes is derived from the *boto*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] They are derived from *Sotalia guianensis*, are most likely harvested along the coast and the Amazon River delta, and then are traded up the Amazon River.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/amazon-river-dolphin] In inland cities far from the coast, many, if not most, of the fetishes are derived from domestic animals such as sheep and pigs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] While blue macaws have been known from taxidermic and captive specimens since at least 1790, location of the Lear's macaw's endemic habitat wasn't known until 1978.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] The glaucous macaw was extirpated in the 1800s by clearance for agriculture and cattle grazing of the yatay palm (*Butia yatay*) groves upon which it fed, though rumors of its continued existence persist.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] Lear's macaws have made a comeback from near extinction in the early 1980s (about 60 birds) to over 1000 as a result of conservation programs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] Hyacinth macaws remain locally common within parts of their range, but their range has become fragmented into three known distinct populations in southern Brazil, eastern Bolivia and northeastern Paraguay; populations are declining due to extensive trapping for the pet trade as well as habitat loss.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] All *Anodorhynchus* macaws are listed on CITES Appendix I.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] The genus, *Anodorhynchus* Spix, 1824 is one of six genera of Central and South American macaws in tribe *Arini* of macaws, parakeets and closely related genera.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] The macaws and parakeets comprise the clade of long-tailed parrots which with sister clade the short-tailed Amazonian parrots and allies make up subfamily *Arinae* of Neotropical parrots in family *Psittacidae* of true parrots.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] Some recent commentators have suggested that the allopatric Lear's macaw and glaucous macaw should be considered conspecifics.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/anodorhynchus] In the absence of a specimen, Rothschild scientifically described and named it as a separate species based on the evidence that violet macaws were said to have inhabited the island of Guadeloupe; however, they were probably hyacinth macaws imported from the mainland of South America.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The **Asian elephant** (***Elephas maximus***), also known as the **Asiatic elephant**, is the only living species in the genus *Elephas*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is the largest living land animal in Asia and the second largest living elephantid in the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is characterised by its long trunk with a single finger-like process; large tusks in males; laterally folded large ears and wrinkled grey skin that is partly depigmented on the trunk, ears or neck.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Adult males average 4 t (4.4 short tons) in weight and females 2.7 t (3.0 short tons).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It has a large and well developed neocortex of the brain, is highly intelligent and self-aware, being able to display behaviours associated with grief, learning and greeting.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Three subspecies are recognised—*E. m. maximus*, *E. m. indicus* and *E. m. sumatranus*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant is distributed in the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia, from India in the west to Borneo in the east, and Nepal in the north to Sumatra in the south.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It inhabits grasslands, tropical evergreen forests, semi-evergreen forests, moist deciduous forests, dry deciduous forests and dry thorn forests.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is herbivorous, eating about 150 kg (330 lb) of vegetation per day.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Cows and calves form groups, while males remain solitary or form "bachelor groups" with other males.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During the breeding season, males temporarily join female groups to mate.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Wild Asian elephants live to be about 60 years old.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] While female captive elephants are recorded to have lived beyond 60 years when kept in semi-natural surroundings, Asian elephants die at a much younger age in captivity; captive populations are declining due to a low birth and high death rate.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Since 1986, the Asian elephant has been listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List, as the population has declined by at least 50% over the last three elephant generations, which is about 60–75 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is primarily threatened by loss of habitat, habitat degradation, fragmentation and poaching.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The earliest indications of captive use of Asian elephants are engravings on seals of the Indus Valley civilisation dated to the 3rd millennium BC.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Carl Linnaeus proposed the scientific name *Elephas maximus* in 1758 in the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*, the foundational work of modern zoological taxonomy.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Carl Linnaeus based his description on a variety of sources and specimens, some of which were later shown to be African elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Linnaeus's description heavily relied on a 1693 description of an elephant skeleton by John Ray.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This skeleton still exists within the collection of the Natural History Museum of the University of Florence, and almost certainly represents that of Hansken, a female Asian elephant from Sri Lanka that toured Europe in the 17th century.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This specimen was declared to be the lectotype specimen for the species in 2014.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] *Elephas indicus* was proposed by Georges Cuvier in 1798, who described an elephant from India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Coenraad Jacob Temminck named an elephant from Sumatra *Elephas sumatranus* in 1847.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Frederick Nutter Chasen classified all three as subspecies of the Asian elephant in 1940.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] These three subspecies are recognised as valid taxa.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Results of phylogeographic and morphological analyses indicate that the Sri Lankan and Indian elephants are not distinct enough to warrant classification as separate subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Sri Lankan elephants are the largest subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Their skin colour is darker than of *E. m. indicus* and of *E. m. sumatranus* with larger and more distinct patches of depigmentation on ears, face, trunk and belly.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The skin color of the Indian elephant is generally grey and lighter than that of *E. m. maximus* but darker than that of *E. m. sumatranus*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A potential fourth subspecies, the Borneo elephant (*Elephas maximus borneensis*), occurs in Borneo's northeastern parts, primarily in Sabah (Malaysia), and sometimes in Kalimantan (Indonesia).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It was proposed by Paules Deraniyagala in 1950, who described an elephant in an illustration published in the *National Geographic* magazine, but not as a living elephant in accordance with the rules of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] These elephants living in northern Borneo are smaller than all the other subspecies, but had larger ears, a longer tail, and straight tusks.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Results of genetic analysis indicate that their ancestors separated from the mainland population about 300,000 years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The genus *Elephas*, of which the Asian elephant is the only living member, is the closest relative of the extinct mammoths.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The two groups are estimated to have split from each other around 7 million years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] *Elephas* originated in Sub-Saharan Africa during the Pliocene and spread throughout Africa before expanding into the southern half of Asia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The earliest *Elephas* species, *Elephas ekorensis*, is known from the Early Pliocene of East Africa, around 5–4.2 million years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Skeletal remains of *E. m. asurus* have been recorded from the Middle East: Iran, Iraq, Syria, and Turkey from periods dating between at least 1800 BC and likely 700 BC.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In general, the Asian elephant is smaller than the African bush elephant and has the highest body point on the head.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The ears are small with dorsal borders folded laterally.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It has up to 20 pairs of ribs and 34 caudal vertebrae.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The feet have five nail-like structures on each forefoot, and four on each hind foot.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The forehead has two hemispherical bulges, unlike the flat front of the African elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Its long trunk or proboscis has only one fingerlike tip, in contrast to the African elephants, which have two.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Hence, the Asian species relies more on wrapping around a food item and squeezing it into its mouth, rather than grasping with the tip.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants have more muscle coordination and can perform more complex tasks.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Cows usually lack tusks; if tusks—in that case, called "tushes"—are present, they are barely visible and only seen when the mouth is open.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The enamel plates of the molars are greater in number and closer together in Asian elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Some bulls may also lack tusks; these individuals are called "makhnas" and are especially common among the Sri Lankan elephant population.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A tusk from an 11 ft (3.4 m) tall elephant killed by Sir Victor Brooke measured 8 ft (2.4 m) in length, and nearly 17 in (43 cm) in circumference, and weighed 90 lb (41 kg).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This tusk's weight is, however, exceeded by the weight of a shorter tusk of about 6 ft (1.8 m) in length, which weighed 100 lb (45 kg), and there have reportedly been tusks weighing over 150 lb (68 kg).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Skin colour is usually grey, and may be masked by soil because of dusting and wallowing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Their wrinkled skin is movable and contains many nerve centres.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is smoother than that of African elephants and may be depigmented on the trunk, ears, or neck.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The epidermis and dermis of the body average 18 mm (0.71 in) thick; skin on the dorsum is 30 mm (1.2 in) thick providing protection against bites, bumps, and adverse weather.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Its folds increase surface area for heat dissipation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They can tolerate cold better than excessive heat.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] On average, when fully-grown, bulls are about 2.75 m (9 ft 0 in) tall at the shoulder and 4.0 t (4.4 short tons) in weight, while cows are smaller at about 2.40 m (7 ft 10 in) at the shoulder and 2.7 t (3.0 short tons) in weight.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Sexual dimorphism in body size is relatively less pronounced in Asian elephants than in African bush elephants; with bulls averaging 15% and 23% taller in the former and latter respectively.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Length of body and head including trunk is 5.5–6.5 m (18–21 ft) with the tail being 1.2–1.5 m (3 ft 11 in – 4 ft 11 in) long.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The largest bull elephant ever recorded was shot by the Maharajah of Susang in the Garo Hills of Assam, India, in 1924, it weighed an estimated 7 t (7.7 short tons), stood 3.43 m (11.3 ft) tall at the shoulder and was 8.06 m (26.4 ft) long from head to tail.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Raja Gaj elephant in Bardia National Park was estimated to be 3.4 m (11.3 ft) tall at the shoulder and one of the biggest Asian bull elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] There are reports of larger individuals as tall as 3.66 m (12.0 ft) and 2.92 m (9 ft 7 in), and 7.99 m (26.2 ft) long from head to tail.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants are distributed throughout the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia, from India in the west, to Borneo in the east, and Nepal in the north, to Sumatra in the south.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They inhabit grasslands, tropical evergreen forests, semi-evergreen forests, moist deciduous forests, dry deciduous forests and dry thorn forests, in addition to cultivated and secondary forests and scrublands.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Over this range of habitat types elephants occur from sea level to over 3,000 m (9,800 ft).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In the eastern Himalaya in northeast India, they regularly move up above 3,000 m (9,800 ft) in summer at a few sites.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In Bangladesh, some isolated populations survived in the south-east Chittagong Hills in the early 1990s.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In Malaysia's northern Johor and Terengganu National Park, two Asian elephants tracked using satellite tracking technology spent most of their time in secondary or "logged-over forest"; they travelled 75% of their time in an area less than 1.5 km (0.93 mi) away from a water source.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In China, the Asian elephant survives only in the prefectures of Xishuangbanna, Simao and Lincang of southern Yunnan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As of 2020, the estimated population was around 300 individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As of 2017, the estimated wild population in India account for nearly three-fourths of the extant population, at 27,312 individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In 2019, the Asian elephant population in India increased to an estimated 27,000–29,000 individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As of 2019, the global wild population was estimated at 48,323–51,680 individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They are classified as megaherbivores and consume up to 150 kg (330 lb) of plant matter per day.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Around 50 to 75% of the day is devoted to eating.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They are generalist feeders, and are both grazers and browsers.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They are known to feed on at least 112 different plant species, most commonly of the order Malvales, as well as the legume, palm, sedge and true grass families.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They browse more in the dry season with bark constituting a major part of their diet in the cool part of that season.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They drink at least once a day and are never far from a permanent source of fresh water.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They need 80–200 litres of water a day and use even more for bathing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] At times, they scrape the soil for clay or minerals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Cows and calves move about together as groups, while bulls disperse from their mothers upon reaching adolescence.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Bulls are solitary or form temporary "bachelor groups".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Cow-calf units generally tend to be small, typically consisting of three adults (most likely related females) and their offspring.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Larger groups of as many as 15 adult females have also been recorded.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Seasonal aggregations of 17 individuals including calves and young adults have been observed in Sri Lanka's Uda Walawe National Park.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Until recently, Asian elephants, like African elephants, were thought to be under the leadership of older adult females, or matriarchs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is now recognized that cows form extensive and very fluid social networks, with varying degrees of associations between individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Social ties generally tend to be weaker than in African bush elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Unlike African elephants, which rarely use their forefeet for anything other than digging or scraping soil, Asian elephants are more agile at using their feet in conjunction with the trunk for manipulating objects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They can sometimes be known for their violent behavior.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants are recorded to make three basic sounds: growls, squeaks and snorts.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Growls in their basic form are used for short distance communication.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During mild arousal, growls resonate in the trunk and become rumbles while for long-distance communication, they escalate into roars.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Low-frequency growls are infrasonic and made in many contexts.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Squeaks come in two forms: chirpings and trumpets.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Chirping consists of multiple short squeaks and signals conflict and nervousness.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Trumpets are lengthened squeaks with increased loudness and are produced during extreme arousal.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Snorts signal changes in activity and increase in loudness during mild or strong arousal.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During the latter case, when an elephant bounces the tip of the trunk, it creates booms which serve as threat displays.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants can distinguish low-amplitude sounds.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Rarely, tigers have been recorded attacking and killing calves, especially if the calves become separated from their mothers, stranded from their herd, or orphaned.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Adults are largely invulnerable to natural predation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] There is a singular anecdotal case of a mother Asian elephant allegedly being killed alongside her calf; however, this account is contestable.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants appear to distinguish between the growls of larger predators like tigers and smaller predators like leopards; they react to leopards less fearfully and more aggressively.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Reproduction in Asian elephants can be attributed to the production and perception of signaling compounds called pheromones.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] These signals are transmitted through various bodily fluids.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They are commonly released in urine but in males they are also found in special secretions from the temporal glands.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Once integrated and perceived, these signals provide the receiver with information about the reproductive status of the sender.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] If both parties are ready to breed, reproductive ritualic behavior occurs and the process of sexual reproduction proceeds.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Bulls will fight one another to get access to oestrus cows.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Strong fights over access to females are extremely rare.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Bulls reach sexual maturity around the age of 12–15.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Between the ages of 10 and 20 years, bulls undergo an annual phenomenon known as "musth".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This is a period where the testosterone level is up to 100 times greater than non-musth periods, and they become aggressive.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Secretions containing pheromones occur during this period, from the paired temporal glands located on the head between the lateral edge of the eye and the base of the ear.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The aggressive behaviors observed during musth can be attributed to varying amounts of frontalin (1,5-dimethyl-6,8-dioxabicyclo[3.2.1]octane) throughout the maturation process of bulls.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Frontalin is a pheromone that was first isolated in bark beetles but can also be produced in the bulls of both Asian and African Elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The compound can be excreted through urine as well as through the temporal glands of the bull, allowing signaling to occur.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During musth, increased concentrations of frontalin in the bull's urine communicate the reproductive status of the bull to female elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Similar to other mammals, hormone secretion in female elephants is regulated by an estrous cycle.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This cycle is regulated by surges in Luteinizing hormone that are observed three weeks from each other.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This type of estrous cycle has also been observed in African Elephants but is not known to affect other mammals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The first surge in Luteinizing hormone is not followed by the release of an egg from the ovaries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] However, some female elephants still exhibit the expected mating protocols during this surge.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Female elephants give ovulatory cues by utilizing sex pheromones.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A principal component thereof, (Z)-7-dodecen-1-yl acetate, has also been found to be a sex pheromone in numerous species of insects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In both insects and elephants, this chemical compound is used as an attractant to assist the mating process.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In elephants, the chemical is secreted through urination and this aids in the attraction of bulls to mate.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Once detected, the chemical stimulates the vomeronasal organ of the bull, thus providing information on the maturity of the female.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Reproductive signaling exchange between male and female elephants are transmitted through olfactory cues in bodily fluids.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In males, the increase in frontalin during musth heightens their sensitivity to the (Z)-7-dodecen-1-yl acetate produced by female elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Once perceived by receptors in the trunk, a sequence of ritualistic behaviors follow.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The responses in males vary based on both the stage of development and the temperament of the elephant.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This process of receiving and processing signals through the trunk is referred to as flehmen.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The difference in body movements give cues to gauge if the male is interested in breeding with the female that produced the secretion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A bull that is ready to breed will move closer to the urine and in some cases an erection response is elicited.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A bull that is not ready to breed will be timid and try to dissociate themselves from the signal.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In addition to reproductive communication, chemosensory signaling is used to facilitate same-sex interactions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] When less developed males detect pheromones from a male in musth, they often retreat to avoid coming in contact with aggressive behaviors.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Female elephants have also been seen to communicate with each other through pheromone in urine.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The purpose of this type of intrasex communication is still being investigated.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] However, there are clear differences in signaling strength and receiver response throughout different stages of the estrous cycle.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The gestation period is 18–22 months, and the cow gives birth to one calf, only occasionally twins.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The calf is fully developed by the 19th month, but stays in the womb to grow so that it can reach its mother to feed.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] At birth, the calf weighs about 100 kg (220 lb), and is suckled for up to three years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Once a female gives birth, she usually does not breed again until the first calf is weaned, resulting in a four to five-year birth interval.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During this period, mother to calf communication primarily takes place through temporal means.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] However, male calves have been known to develop sex pheromone-producing organs at a young age.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Early maturity of the vomeronasal organ allows immature elephants to produce and receive pheromones.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is unlikely that the integration of these pheromones will result in a flehmen response in a calf.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Females stay on with the herd, but mature males are chased away.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Female Asian elephants sexually mature around the age of 10~15 and keep growing until 30, while males fully mature at more than the age of 25, and constantly grow throughout their life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Average elephant life expectancy is approximately 60 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Some individuals are known to have lived into their late 80s.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Generation length of the Asian elephant is 22 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants have a very large and highly developed neocortex, a trait also shared by humans, apes and certain dolphin species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They have a greater volume of cerebral cortex available for cognitive processing than all other existing land animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Results of studies indicate that Asian elephants have cognitive abilities for tool use and tool-making similar to great apes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They exhibit a wide variety of behaviours, including those associated with grief, learning, allomothering, mimicry, play, altruism, use of tools, compassion, cooperation, self-awareness, memory, and language.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants reportedly head to safer ground during natural disasters like tsunamis and earthquakes, but data from two satellite-collared Sri Lankan elephants indicate this may be untrue.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Several students of elephant cognition and neuroanatomy are convinced that Asian elephants are highly intelligent and self-aware.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The pre-eminent threats to the Asian elephant today are the loss, degradation and fragmentation of its habitat, which leads to increasing conflicts between humans and elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants are poached for ivory and a variety of other products including meat and leather.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The demand for elephant skin has risen due to it being an increasingly-common ingredient in traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In some parts of Asia, people and elephants have co-existed for thousands of years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In other areas, people and elephants come into conflict, resulting in violence, and ultimately, the displacement of elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The main causes of human-elephant conflict includes the growing human population, large-scale development projects and poor top-down governance.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Proximate causes includes habitat loss due to deforestation, disruption of elephant migratory routes, expansion of agriculture and illegal encroachment into protected areas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Destruction of forests through logging, encroachment, slash-and-burn, shifting cultivation, and monoculture tree plantations are major threats to the survival of elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Human–elephant conflicts occur when elephants raid crops of shifting cultivators in fields, which are scattered over a large area interspersed with forests.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Depredation in human settlements is another major area of human–elephant conflict occurring in small forest pockets, encroachments into elephant habitat, and on elephant migration routes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] However, studies in Sri Lanka indicate that traditional slash-and-burn agriculture may create optimal habitats for elephants by creating a mosaic of successional-stage vegetation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Populations inhabiting small habitat fragments are much more liable to come into conflict with humans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Development such as border fencing along the India–Bangladesh border has become a major impediment to the free movement of elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In Assam, more than 1,150 humans and 370 elephants died as a result of human-elephant conflict between 1980 and 2003.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In a 2010 study, it was estimated that in India alone, over 400 people were killed by elephants each year, and 0.8 to 1 million hectares were damaged, affecting at least 500,000 families across the country.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Moreover, elephants are known to destroy crops worth up to US$2–3 million annually.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This has major impacts on the welfare and livelihoods of local communities, as well as the future conservation of this species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In countries like Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, the Asian elephant is one of the most feared wild animals, even though they are less deadly than other local animals such as venomous snakes (which were estimated to claim more than 30 times more lives in Sri Lanka than elephants).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As a whole, Asian elephants display highly sophisticated and sometimes unpredictable behaviour.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Most untamed elephants try to avoid humans, but if they are caught off guard by any perceived physical threat, including humans, they will likely charge.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This is especially true of males in musth and of females with young.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Gunfire and other similar methods of deterring, which are known to be effective against many kinds of wild animals including tigers, may or may not work with elephants, and can even worsen the situation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants that have been abused by humans in the past often become "rogue elephants", which regularly attack people with no provocation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The demand for ivory during the 1970s and 1980s, particularly in East Asia, led to rampant poaching and the serious decline of elephants in both Africa and Asia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In Thailand, the illegal trade in live elephants and ivory still flourishes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Although the amount of ivory being openly sold has decreased substantially since 2001, Thailand still has one of the largest and most active black markets for ivory seen anywhere in the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Tusks from Thai-poached elephants also enter the market; between 1992 and 1997 at least 24 male elephants were killed for their tusks.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Up to the early 1990s, Vietnamese ivory craftsmen used exclusively Asian elephant ivory from Vietnam and neighbouring Lao and Cambodia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Before 1990, there were few tourists and the low demand for worked ivory could be supplied by domestic elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Economic liberalisation and an increase in tourism raised both local and visitors' demands for worked ivory, which resulted in heavy poaching.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The skin of the Asian elephant is used as an ingredient in Chinese medicine as well as in the manufacture of ornamental beads.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The practice has been aided by China's State Forestry Administration (SFA), which has issued licences for the manufacture and sale of pharmaceutical products containing elephant skin, thereby making trading legal.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In 2010, four skinned elephants were found in a forest in Myanmar; 26 elephants were killed by poachers in 2013 and 61 in 2016.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] According to the NGO Elephant Family, Myanmar is the main source of elephant skin, where a poaching crisis has developed rapidly since 2010.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The elephant endotheliotropic herpesvirus (EEHV) is a member of the *Proboscivirus* genus, a novel clade most closely related to the mammalian betaherpesviruses.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As of 2011, it is responsible for as many as 70 deaths of both zoo and wild Asian elephants worldwide, especially in young calves.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In particular, several incidents of calves dying from elephant endotheliotropic herpesvirus have been recorded in Myanmar.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The elephant schistosome is a parasitic trematode that uses the Asian elephant as a definitive host.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Two other hosts may be the Indian elephant and the greater one-horned rhinoceros.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants are protected across various geographies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant is listed on CITES Appendix I.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is a quintessential flagship species, deployed to catalyze a range of conservation goals, including habitat conservation at landscape scales, generating public awareness on conservation issues, and mobilisation as a popular cultural icon both in India and the West.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] A key aspect of conservation is connectivity of the preferred movement routes of Asian elephants through areas with high vegetation cover and low human population density.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The World Elephant Day is celebrated annually on 12 August since 2012.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Events are organized to divulge information and to engage people about the problems that the Asian elephant is facing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] August has been established as the Asian Elephant Awareness Month by zoos and conservation partners in the United States.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Karnataka state in India hosts the most Asian elephants of any known area, comprising around 20% of the total population in the country.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The distribution of elephants in the state according to one estimate is roughly 38,310 km2 (14,790 sq mi).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In a 2013 study, an estimated 10, 000 elephants inhabited the Western Ghats, and were primarily threatened by poaching and habitat fragmentation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] An increase in conflict with humans was also cited as a likely issue.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Conservation plans aimed to establish wildlife corridors, stop poaching of bulls, and protect or manage land area.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Project Elephant was initiated in 1992 as a Centrally Sponsored Scheme (CSS) by the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change of the Government of India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The project was initiated to protect the Indian elephant and its habitats and to establish dedicated elephant reserves for sustaining elephant populations.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The distribution of elephants in Sri Lanka is only two-fifths of what it was in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Due to this decrease, interactions with humans occur much more frequently.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] During a 2003 survey, the local people expressed some form of disapproval towards the conservation of Asian elephants as farmers viewed them as pests, however, most of the participants were supportive of the idea.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In China, Asian elephants are under first-level protection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Yunnan province has 11 national and regional nature reserves.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In total, the covered protected area in China is about 510,000 ha (1,300,000 acres).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In 2020, the population of Asian elephants in Yunnan was estimated at around 300 individuals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] As conflicts between humans and wild elephants have emerged around protected areas in the last years, the prefecture of Xishuangbanna built food bases and planted bananas and bamboo to create a better habitat.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In Thailand, Salakpra Wildlife Sanctuary and Tham Than Lot National Park are protected areas hosting around 250–300 elephants, according to figures from 2013.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In recent years the National Park has faced issues due to encroachment and over-exploitation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In India, the National Board of Wildlife recommended to allow coal mining in Dehing Patkai National Park in April 2020.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The decision raised concerns between students and environmental activists who launched an online campaign to stop the project.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] About half of the global zoo elephant population is kept in European zoos, where they have less than half (18.9 years) the median life span of conspecifics (41.6 years) in protected populations in range countries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] This discrepancy is clearest in Asian elephants: infant mortality is more than two to three times that seen in Burmese timber camps, and adult survivorship in zoos has not improved significantly in recent years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] One risk factor for Asian zoo elephants is being moved between institutions, with early removal from the mother tending to have additional adverse effects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Another risk factor is being born into a zoo rather than being imported from the wild, with poor adult survivorship in zoo-born Asians apparently being conferred prenatally or in early infancy.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Likely causes for compromised survivorship is stress and/or obesity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Foot problems are commonly observed in captive elephants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] These are related to lack of exercise, long hours standing on hard substrates, and contamination resulting from standing in their dung.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] However, mistreatment may lead to serious disability or death.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Demographic analysis of captive Asian elephants in North America indicates that the population is not self-sustaining.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] First year mortality is nearly 30 per cent, and fecundity is extremely low throughout the prime reproductive years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Data from North American and European regional studbooks from 1962 to 2006 were analysed for deviations in the birth and juvenile death sex ratios.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Of 349 captive calves born, 142 died prematurely.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They died within one month of birth, major causes being stillbirth and infanticide by either the calf's mother or by one of the exhibition mates.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The sex ratio of stillbirths in Europe was found to have a tendency for excess of males.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Young elephants are captured from the wild and illegally imported to Thailand from Myanmar for use in the tourism industry; calves are used mainly in amusement parks and are trained to perform various stunts for tourists.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The calves are often subjected to a 'breaking in' process, which may involve being tied up, confined, starved, beaten and tortured; as a result, two-thirds may perish.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Handlers use a technique known as the training crush, in which "handlers use sleep-deprivation, hunger, and thirst to 'break' the elephants' spirit and make them submissive to their owners"; moreover, handlers drive nails into the elephants' ears and feet.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant is the national animal of Thailand and Laos.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It has also been declared as the national heritage animal of India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Bones of Asian elephants excavated at Mohenjo-daro in the Indus Valley indicate that they were tamed in the Indus Valley Civilisation and used for work.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Decorated elephants are also depicted on seals and were modelled in clay.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant became a siege engine, a mount in war, a status symbol, a beast of burden, and an elevated platform for hunting during historical times in South Asia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Asian elephants have been captured from the wild and tamed for use by humans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants can remember tone, melody, and words, allowing them to recognise more than 20 verbal commands.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Their ability to work under instruction makes them particularly useful for carrying heavy objects.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They have been used particularly for timber-carrying in jungle areas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Other than their work use, they have been used in war, in ceremonies, and for carriage.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] It is reported that war elephants are still used by the Kachin Independence Army (KIA) in Kachin State in northern Myanmar against Myanmar's military.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The KIA use about four dozen elephants to carry supplies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant plays an important part in the culture of the subcontinent and beyond, being featured prominently in the *Panchatantra* fables and the Buddhist *Jataka* tales.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] They play a major role in Hinduism: the god Ganesha's head is that of an elephant, and the "blessings" of a temple elephant are highly valued.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Elephants are frequently used in processions where the animals are adorned with festive outfits.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The Asian elephant is depicted in several Indian manuscripts and treatises with notable amongst these including *Matanga Lila* (elephant sport) of Nilakantha.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] The manuscript *Hastividyarnava* is from Assam in northeast India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] In the Burmese, Thai and Sinhalese animal and planetary zodiac, the Asian elephant, both tusked and tuskless, are the fourth and fifth animal zodiacs of the Burmese, the fourth animal zodiac of the Thai, and the second animal zodiac of the Sinhalese people of Sri Lanka.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/asian-elephant] Similarly, the elephant is the twelfth animal zodiac in the Dai animal zodiac of the Dai people in southern China.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] A **biodiversity action plan** (**BAP**) is an internationally recognized program aimed at protecting and restoring threatened species and habitats, and at strengthening the resilience of biological systems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The concept emerged from the 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which called on participating nations to develop strategies for conserving biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] As of 2009, 191 countries had ratified the CBD, although only a portion of them had produced comprehensive BAP documents.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] A fundamental method of engagement to a BAP is thorough documentation regarding individual species, with emphasis upon the population distribution and conservation status.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] This task, while fundamental, is highly daunting, since only an estimated ten percent of the world's species are believed to have been characterized as of 2006, most of these unknowns being fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and plants.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] For many bird, mammal and reptile species, information is often available in published literature; however, for fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and many plants, such information may require considerable local data collection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] It is also useful to compile time trends of population estimates in order to understand the dynamics of population variability and vulnerability.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In some parts of the world complete species inventories are not realistic; for example, in the Madagascar dry deciduous forests, many species are completely undocumented and much of the region has never even been systematically explored by scientists.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] A species plan component of a country's BAP should ideally entail a thorough description of the range, habitat, behaviour, breeding and interaction with other species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Once a determination has been made of conservation status (e.g. rare, endangered, threatened, vulnerable), a plan can then be created to conserve and restore the species population to target levels.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan should also articulate which public and private agencies should implement the protection strategy and indicate budgets available to execute this strategy.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Agricultural practices can reduce the biodiversity of a region significantly.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity Action Plans for agricultural production are necessary to ensure a biodiversity friendly production.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] It has not been common for companies to integrate biodiversity aspects into their value chain, but some companies and organizations have shown overall efforts for implementing better practices.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] An existing example for guidelines on biodiversity practices in agriculture is the Biodiversity Action Plan for spice production in India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] By planning and implementing biodiversity friendly measures, farmers can mitigate negative impacts and support positive influences.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Where a number of threatened species depend upon a specific habitat, it may be appropriate to prepare a habitat protection element of the Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Examples of such special habitats are: raised acidic bogs of Scotland; Waterberg Biosphere bushveld in South Africa; California's coastal wetlands; and Sweden's Stora Alvaret on the island of Öland.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In this case also, careful inventories of species and also the geographic extent and quality of the habitat must be documented.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Then, as with species plans, a program can be created to protect, enhance and/or restore habitat using similar strategies as discussed above under the species plans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Some examples of individual countries which have produced substantive Biodiversity Action Plans follow.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In every example the plans concentrate on plants and vertebrate animals, with very little attention to neglected groups such as fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms, even though these are also part of biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Preparation of a country BAP may cost up to 100 million pounds sterling, with annual maintenance costs roughly ten percent of the initial cost.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] If plans took into account neglected groups, the cost would be higher.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Obviously costs for countries with small geographical area or simplified ecosystems have a much lesser cost.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP has been costed in the area of several million pounds sterling.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Australia has developed a detailed and rigorous Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] This document estimates that the total number of indigenous species may be 560,000, many of which are endemic.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] A key element of the BAP is protection of the Great Barrier Reef, which is actually in a much higher state of health than most of the world's reefs, Australia having one of the highest percentages of treated wastewater.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] There are however serious ongoing concerns, particularly in regards to the ongoing negative impact on water quality from land use practices.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Also, climate change impact is feared to be significant.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Considerable analysis has been conducted on the sustainable yield of firewood production, a major threat to deforestation in most tropical countries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Biological inventory work; assessment of harvesting practices; and computer modeling of the dynamics of treefall, rot and harvest; have been carried out to adduce data on safe harvesting rates.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Extensive research has also been conducted on the relation of brush clearance to biodiversity decline and impact on water tables; for example, these effects have been analyzed in the Toolibin Lake wetlands region.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] New Zealand has ratified the Convention on Biological Diversity and as part of The New Zealand Biodiversity Strategy and Biodiversity Action Plans are implemented on ten separate themes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Local government and some companies also have their own Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP recognizes impacts of large numbers of tourists to the marine and coastal diversity of the Soufrière area of the country.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The BAP specifically acknowledges that the carrying capacity for human use and water pollution discharge of sensitive reef areas was exceeded by the year 1990.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan also addresses conservation of the historic island fishing industry.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In 1992, several institutions in conjunction with native fishermen to produce a sustainable management plan for fishery resources, embodied in the Soufrière Marine Management Area.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP features significant involvement from the University of the West Indies.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Specific detailed attention is given to three species of threatened marine turtles, to a variety of vulnerable birds and a number of pelagic fishes and cetaceans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of habitat conservation the plan focusses attention on the biologically productive mangrove swamps and notes that virtually all mangrove areas had already come under national protection by 1984.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The Tanzania national BAP addresses issues related to sustainable use of Lake Manyara, an extensive freshwater lake, whose usage by humans accelerated in the period 1950 to 1990.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The designation of the Lake Manyara Biosphere Reserve under UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme in 1981 combines conservation of the lake and surrounding high value forests with sustainable use of the wetlands area and simple agriculture.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] This BAP has united principal lake users in establishing management targets.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The biosphere reserve has induced sustainable management of the wetlands, including monitoring groundwater and the chemistry of the escarpment water source.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan covers not only terrestrial species associated with lands within the UK, but also marine species and migratory birds, which spend a limited time in the UK or its offshore waters.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The UK plan encompasses "391 Species Action Plans, 45 Habitat Action Plans and 162 Local Biodiversity Action Plans with targeted actions".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] This plan is noteworthy because of its extensive detail, clarity of endangerment mechanisms, specificity of actions, follow up monitoring program and its inclusion of migrating cetaceans and pelagic birds.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] On August 28, 2007, the new Biodiversity Action Plan (BAP) [launched in 1997] identified 1,149 species and 65 habitats in the UK that needed conservation and greater protection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The updated list included the hedgehog, house sparrow, grass snake and the garden tiger moth, while otters, bottlenose dolphins and red squirrels remained in need of habitat protection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In May 2011, the European Commission adopted a new strategy to halt the loss of biodiversity and ecosystem services in the EU by 2020, in line with the commitments made at the 10th meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) held in Nagoya, Japan in 2010.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In 2012 the UK BAP was succeeded by the 'UK Post-2010 Biodiversity Framework'.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] To support the work of the UK BAP, the UK BAP website was created by JNCC in 2001.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The website contained information on the BAP process, hosted all relevant documents, and provided news and relevant updates.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In March 2011, as part of the UK government's review of websites, the UK BAP site was ‘closed’, and the core content was migrated into the JNCC website.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Content from the original UK BAP website has been archived by the National Archives as snapshots from various dates (for example, UK *BAP*: copy March 2011; copy 2012).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Twenty-six years prior to the international biodiversity convention, the United States had launched a national program to protect threatened species in the form of the 1966 Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The legislation created broad authority for analyzing and listing species of concern, and mandated that Species Recovery Plans be created.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Thus, while the USA is an unratified signer of the accord, arguably it has the longest track record and most comprehensive program of species protection of any country.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] There are about 7000 listed species (e.g. endangered or threatened), of which about half have approved Recovery Plans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] While this number of species seems high compared to other countries, the value is rather indicative of the total number of species characterized, which is extremely large.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Five major divisions of habitat have been identified in Uzbekistan’s BAP: Wetlands (including reed habitat and man-made marsh); desert ecosystems (including sandy, stony and clay); steppes; riparian ecosystems; and mountain ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Over 27,000 species have been inventoried in the country, with a high rate of endemism for fishes and reptiles.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Principal threats to biodiversity are related to human activities associated with overpopulation and generally related to agricultural intensification.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Major geographic regions encompassed by the BAP include the Aral Sea Programme (threatened by long-term drainage and salination, largely for cotton production), the Nuratau Biosphere Reserve, and the Western Tien Shan Mountains Programme (in conjunction with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Some developing countries criticize the emphasis of BAPs, because these plans inherently favour consideration of wildlife protection above food and industrial production, and in some cases may represent an obstacle to population growth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The plans are costly to produce, a fact which makes it difficult for many smaller countries and poorer countries to comply.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of the plans themselves, many countries have adopted pro-forma plans including little research and even less in the way of natural resource management.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Almost universally, this has resulted in plans which emphasize plants and vertebrate animals, and which overlook fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] With regard to specific world regions, there is a notable lack of substantive participation by most of the Middle Eastern countries and much of Africa, the latter of which may be impeded by economic considerations of plan preparation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Some governments such as the European Union have diverted the purpose of a biodiversity action plan, and implemented the convention accord by a set of economic development policies with referencing certain ecosystems' protection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The definition of biodiversity under the Convention on Biological Diversity now recognises that biodiversity is a combination of ecosystem structure and function, as much as its components e.g. species, habitats and genetic resources.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity and wildlife are not the same thing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The traditional focus on threatened species in BAPs is at odds with the principles of biodiversity management because, by the time species become threatened, the processes that maintain biodiversity are already compromised.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Individual species are also regarded as generally poor indicators of biodiversity when it comes to actual planning.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] A species approach to BAPs only serves to identify and at best, apply a patch to existing problems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Increasingly, biodiversity planners are looking through the lens of ecosystem services.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Critics of biodiversity are often confusing the need to protect species (their intrinsic value) with the need to maintain ecosystem processes, which ultimately maintain human society and do not compromise economic development.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Hence, a core principle of biodiversity management, that traditional BAPs overlook, is the need to incorporate cultural, social and economic values in the process.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Modern day BAPs use an analysis of ecosystem services, key ecological process drivers, and use species as one of many indicators of change.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] They would seek to maintain structure and function by addressing habitat connectivity and resilience and may look at communities of species (threatened or otherwise) as one method of monitoring outcomes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Ultimately, species are the litmus test for biodiversity – viable populations of species can only be expected to exist in relatively intact habitats.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] However, the rationale behind BAPs is to "conserve and restore" biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] One of the fastest developing areas of management is biodiversity offsets.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] The principles are in keeping with ecological impact assessment, which in turn depends on good quality BAPs for evaluation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-action-plan] Contemporary principles of biodiversity management, such as those produced by the Business Biodiversity Offsets Program are now integral to any plans to manage biodiversity, including the development of BAPs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] The IUCN Red List is a list of species which have been assessed according to a system of assigning a global conservation status.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] According to the latest system used by the IUCN, a species can be "Data Deficient" (DD) species – species for which more data and assessment is required before their situation may be determined – as well species comprehensively assessed by the IUCN's species assessment process.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] A species can be "Near Threatened" (NT) and "Least Concern" (LC), these are species which are considered to have relatively robust and healthy populations, according to the assessment authors.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] "Endangered" (EN) species lie between "Vulnerable" (VU) and "Critically Endangered" (CR) species.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] A species must adhere to certain criteria in order to be placed in any of the afore-mentioned conservation status categories, according to the assessment.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] "Threatened" is a category including all those species determined to be Vulnerable, Endangered or Critically Endangered.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] Although in general conversation the terms "endangered species" and "threatened species" may mean other things, for the purposes of the current IUCN system, the List uses the terms "endangered" and "threatened" to denote species to which certain criteria apply.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] Note older or other, such as national, status systems may use other criteria.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] As more information becomes available, or as the conservation status criteria has changed, numerous species have been re-assessed as not endangered, nonetheless the total number of species considered endangered has increased as more new species are assessed for the first time each year.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] According to the 3.1 version of the IUCN conservation status system from 2001, a species is listed as endangered when it meets any of the following criteria from A to E.
[src:endangered-species-iucn-status/endangered-species-iucn-status] A population size reduction of **≥ 50%, projected or suspected to be met within the next 10 years or three generations,** whichever is the longer (up to a maximum of 100 years), based on (and specifying) any of (b) to (e) under A1.
